<P>
CHANGES IN MATH EDUCATION PROPOSED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A group of leading mathematics organizations, warning that American students 
are dangerously unprepared in math, outlined an ambitious plan to revise math 
education that calls for less rote learning and a stronger emphasis on problem 
solving and fundamental concepts and more use of calculators and computers. The 
plan incorporates a number of ideas proposed by math educators in recent years, 
but it is the first coordinated effort to lay out a specific blueprint for 
implementing them. The organizations, working under the auspices of the 
National Research Council, said they would establish teaching standards for 
every grade, rewrite curricula and reconsider the current division of the 
subject into arithmetic, algebra, geometry and other distinct courses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
