<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, A Devastating Scoop du Jour A $3-million job to tear down 41 Balboa 
Naval Hospital buildings spread across 47 acres started Thursday. The 
contractor, Diamond Pacific, expects the task to take a year. Instead of the 
traditional ball and crane, the company chose a Koehring 1466, one of the 
largest machines of its type, to do the bulk of the work. It cost $24,000 just 
to have the machine dismantled in Kansas City, brought here on six 
tractor-trailer rigs and reassembled. Construction began in 1920 on the 
hospital, which grew as demand warranted. In 1988, as part of a land swap with 
San Diego, the Navy unveiled a new hospital in Florida Canyon. DAVE GATLEY / 
Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
