SAN DIEGO SPOTLIGHT: SAN DIEGO ENTERTAINMENT BRIEFS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Soviet conductor Vassili Sinaisky will make his American debut directing the 
San Diego Symphony on Feb. 16 and 18. Sinaisky, the only Soviet conductor to 
win the First Prize Gold Medal at the Von Karajan Competition in Berlin, 
replaces Valery Gergiev, who has been hospitalized, the symphony announced this 
week. Sinaisky, who is a conductor at the Bolshoi Opera Theatre, will conduct 
an all-Russian program featuring San Diego Symphony concertmaster Igor Gruppman 
in Glazunov's Concerto in A Minor. Gruppman was announced as a substitute 
earlier this month for Russian virtuoso, Ilya Grubert, who also had to cancel. 
