<P>
COURT BACKS DETROIT PAPERS' MERGER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The U.S. Court of Appeals today cleared the way for the partial merger of 
Detroit's two daily newspapers, the Free Press and the News. 
</P>
<P>
In a 2-1 decision, the court said a ruling last year by then-Atty. Gen. Edwin 
Meese III approving the joint operating agreement of the two newspapers was 
"based on a permissible construction" of the Newspaper Preservation Act. 
Knight-Ridder Inc., owner of the morning Free Press, has threatened to close 
the paper if the joint operating agreement is not approved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief; Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
