<P>
Part 1; Page 2; Column 1; Late Final Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
94 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
SPORTS; 
</P>
<P>
MAJOR LEAGUES BALK AT BALK RULE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Baseball's controversial balk rule, which created havoc for pitchers during the 
1988 season and led to a 160% increase in balks, is being scrapped for the 1989 
season. 
</P>
<P>
The Major League Baseball Players Assn., which accepted the rule last spring on 
a one-year trial basis, has decided to block it for this season. The Official 
Playing Rules Committee decided to go back to the old rule, which said pitchers 
must come to a "complete stop" instead of a "complete and discernible stop." A 
record 924 balks were called in 1988. The previous record was 356 in 1987. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief; Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
